Commentary.Commentary: The wicket is not very easy, there is some assistance for the bowlers and Pakistan do have dynamic bowling attack. Can they do what the Lankan bowlers did or will the visitors continue to dominate? Stay tuned to find out in a while.

The Sri Lankan coach and captain could not have asked anything better from their bowlers. It was Vishwa Fernando who started things off and then Lahiru Kumara and Lasith Embuldeniya took over. Both finished with 4-fers. The former bowled with pace and got it to nip around and the latter bowled the right pace, got it to turn and both were rewarded. The bowlers will feel their job is done and it is now time for the batters to capitalize.

Pakistan on the other hand, will be very disappointed with how things went out after they elected to bat. Right from the morning session they were probably on the back foot. They lost two early wickets, then there were two 50-plus run stands for wicket 3 and 4 but both could not go on to something significant. Once Azam fell, the procession started. They failed to cross the 200-run mark after being 127 for 3. Just the three batters scoring in double digits out of the 11 is always a sorry scorecard.

What an effort by the Lankans after the break! What an effort by the Lankans overall. High-fives between their players and all smiles for them at the moment as they will be extremely pleased with how things stand at the moment.

What a final hour of the session for the visitors. Pakistan were on top in the first half of the session with Babar Azam and Asad Shafiq taking the charge. Babar looked very strong and got to his fifty but drinks brought in a lapse of concentration for him as soon after he was stumped. The Sri Lankan spinners then started to take charge. They put brakes on the run flow. Haris struggled and just before the end of the session his struggles came to an end. Asad Shafiq is still there unbeaten on 49 and the onus will be on him to bat with the lower order. Lasith Embuldeniya was the star of the session getting both the scalp for the tourists. One would feel it was an even session but Sri Lanka will be the happier of the two sides. What is in store in the final session of the day? Join us after the break to find out.

Flighted delivery on off, Azam defends it off the front foot.
FOUR! Easy pickings this for a man of Babar's caliber. Short outside off, Babar gets on his back foot and creams his punch through covers for a boundary.
Length delivery on middle, Abid flicks it to mid-wicket.
On a length and outside off, Ali plays it to point.
Length delivery on off, Azam taps it towards point for a run.
Again outside off, Babar offers no shot to this one.
On a good length on off, Azam keeps it out.
Outside off, Babar leaves it alone.
Lahiru Kumara is back on. 4-1-9-0 are his figures so far.
Tossed up delivery on middle, Ali defends it off the back foot.
FOUR! Nicely played! Flighted delivery on middle and leg, Abid sweeps it towards fine leg for a boundary.
Loopy delivery on middle, Ali blocks it off the back foot.
Floated delivery on off, Azam punches it through point. The batsmen cross ends.
Flighted delivery on middle, Azam comes down the track and blocks it.
Tossed up delivery on off, Azam defends it off the front foot.
Outside off, Abid offers no shot to this one.
Full delivery outside off, Azam drives it towards covers for a run.
Outside off, Azam shoulders arms to this one.
Good length delivery on middle, Azam blocks it off the front foot.
Outside off, Babar leaves it alone.
On a good length on middle, Azam blocks it off the back foot.
Loopy delivery on off, Ali blocks it off the front foot.
BEATEN! Flighted delivery outside off, Abid looks to defend but misses it due to the turn on this one.
Tossed up delivery on middle, Abid blocks it off the front foot.
Floated delivery on middle, Abid defends it off the back foot.
BEATEN! Flighted delivery just outside off, Abid looks to defend but misses it.
Tossed up delivery on off, Abid plays it to point.
BEATEN! Full delivery outside off, Azam looks to drive but misses it.
On a good length and outside off, Azam shoulders arms to this one.
Bowls it down the leg side, Azam looks to flick but misses it.

FOUR! Nicely played. A little too full on off, Babar waits and then just squeezes it through the gap past gully for a boundary. This is the class of this man. Did not play this shot with power but with just timing and sense. Runs starting to flow here for Pakistan.
On a good length on off, Azam defends it off the back foot.
Full delivery outside off, Babar drives it towards mid off.
Loopy delivery on middle, Ali defends it off the front foot.
Floated delivery on off, Abid plays it to covers.
BEATEN! Beauty of a delivery! Flighted delivery just outside off, Abid looks to defend but misses it due to the spin on this one.
Tossed up delivery on off, Abid defends it off the front foot.

FOUR! Short, wide and punished. Poor start from Embuldeniya. He offers width outside off, Abid quickly gets on his back foot and cuts it through point once again for a boundary. He is super strong in that area and will punish you 9/10 times.
FOUR! Cracking shot. Short delivery outside off, Ali cuts it hard through point for a boundary.
Lasith Embuldeniya is into the attack.

Drinks Break! It has been an excellent hour for Sri Lanka. They have kept it tight and have picked two wickets. Vishwa Fernando has looked superb in the morning. On the other hand, the hosts would hope that Babar Azam and Abid Ali can once again play a similar knock to which they played in Rawalpindi.

NOT OUT! Good use of the review. A full toss from Vishwa around leg. Babar looks to flick but misses and the ball hits him on the pads. The Sri Lankan players go up in a confident appeal and the umpire raises his finger. Babar does not even consult his partner and straightaway signals the 'T'. Replay rolls in and Ultra Edge shows spike as the ball goes past the bat. The on-field umpire will have to overturn his decision. The fans in here take a sigh of relief as their talisman survives.

Big moment in the game. Babar Azam has been adjudged LBW but he has referred it straightaway which indicates there must be some bat involved. Let's see what the replays have to say. Ultra Edge shows spike and Babar survives to the relief of all the fans in Pakistan.
Length delivery on middle, Abid flicks it through mid-wicket. The batsmen take a run.
Outside off, Ali leaves it alone.
Outside off, Ali offers no shot to this one.
FOUR! That is put away! Length delivery outside off, Abid punches it through covers for a boundary.
On a good length and outside off, Ali taps it to point.
On a length on middle, Abid flicks it through mid-wicket. The batsmen cross ends.
SIX! Poor ball this. Half tracker on off and middle. Abid will punish it even in his sleep and he pulls it over the mid-wicket fence for a the first biggie of the game.
On a good length on middle, Abid defends it off the back foot.
FOUR! Nice shot. Length delivery on off, Ali slaps it through covers for a boundary.
Good length delivery on middle, Ali blocks it off the back foot.
On a good length on off, Abid defends it off the front foot.

Skipper Dimuth Karunaratne is into the attack. Looks like maybe it is for a change of ends for someone or there is an elaborate plan because you seldom see someone coming on so early for change of ends. Let's see what the Lankan skipper can offer with the ball.
Bowls it down the leg side, Babar looks to flick but misses it.
On the stumps, Babar defends it with a dead bat.

Excitement from the keeper but not so much from Dickwella. Another one down the leg side, Azam looks to flick but there is two noises. Dickwella dives to his left and catches it. There is an appeal but the umpire turns it down. Replays later on show that the bat hit the pad and the ball kissed the pad.
On a good length on middle, Azam blocks it off the front foot.
FOUR! Babar is off the mark with a boundary. Poor ball this. On the pads, Azam just tickles it fine down the leg side and fetches himself a boundary.
Full delivery down the leg side, Azam looks to flick but misses it. It goes towards the keeper safely.
On a good length on off, Abid blocks it off the front foot.
Full delivery on middle, Ali drives it back towards the bowler and Kumara picks the ball and hits the stumps at the striker's end in his followthrough. But Abid Ali was well in.
Good length delivery on middle, Ali blocks it off the back foot.
FOUR! Beautiful shot this. Good length ball around off, Abid gets on his back foot and punches it gorgeously through covers for a boundary. He is continuing from where he left off in Rawalpindi.
Bowls a bouncer outside leg, Abid does well to duck under it.
On a good length on off, Abid offers a solid defense on this one.
Another length ball outside off and Babar calmly shoulders arms to it. End of a terrific over from Vishwa. Double wicket maiden.
Good length ball outside off, Azam leaves it alone.
One bad ball. After two gems this can be let go. Down the leg side, Babar looks to flick but misses.
The centurion from the last game, Babar Azam joins Abid Ali out in the middle.

OUT! Bowled! Another gem and what an over this is turning out to be. Right through the gate. Vishwa is bowling venom here. Good length ball on off, it comes in to the right-hander. Azhar Ali looks to defend but the ball goes right between the gate of bat and pads to dislodge the off stump. Azhar Ali's poor 2019 continues and the misery piles on him. A silver duck for the skipper. Wicket, dot, wicket. What an over this is turning out to be.
The Pakistan Test skipper starts his innings with a calm leave to begin his innings.
Azhar Ali, the skipper, is the new batsman in.

OUT! Bowled! Beauty of a delivery! WOW! That is every pace bowler's dream delivery. Too good for Shan Masood. Vishwa charges in and shows good seam position. The ball hits the surface and shapes away at the end. Masood looks to defend but gets squared up and the ball hits the top of off pole. Cracker of a delivery to begin the over and Shan's poor series continues. You can watch this delivery on loop and you will never get bored. Shan Masood will not want to watch it though.
On a good length on off, Abid keeps it out.
On a good length on middle, Abid blocks it off the back foot.
Good length delivery on off, Abid defends it off the front foot.
On a good length on middle, Abid blocks it well.
Good length delivery on off, Ali defends it off the back foot.
On a good length on off, Masood punches it towards point. The batsmen take a run.
Wild delivery way outside off. Abid leaves it alone.
FOUR! After a long time Abid Ali is off the mark. Good length ball outside off, Abid cuts it over point and gets off the mark with a boundary. Shot of a man in form.
Good length ball on middle and off, Abid defends it to the right of the bowler.
Finally Vishwa delivers and bowls it on a length on off. Abid defends it towards point.

Once again Abid pulls out of his stride as Vishwa comes charging in. There are fans sitting there which has caused Abid to lose his focus. The umpire has gone near the ropes and he is having a word there.
There is an issue with the sightscreen and hence there is a delay.
Closer to the off pole but still outside so Shan leaves it alone.
Good length ball outside off, it goes away with the angle. Abid does not go chasing after it and lets it carry to the keeper.
Full on off, Masood defends it with a straight bat towards mid on.
On the fourth stump line, SM shoulders arms to it.
Length ball on off, Masood defends it towards point and shouts a loud no.
Short ball outside off, Masood ducks away.

EDGED AND FOUR! First runs off the bat and it has come in a streaky way. First runs in Test cricket in Pakistan for Shan Masood. Beautiful ball this. Good length ball, on the channel of uncertainty. Shan looks to defend but the ball takes the outside edge and goes right in the gap between third slip and gully to the fence for a boundary. This will encourage Lahiru more than Shan.

Stifled appeal but nothing from the umpire. Looked to be high and also pitching outside leg. It is on the pads, Shan looks to flick but misses and gets hit on the pads. The bowler goes up in appeal but the umpire is unmoved.
Even better line. On the off pole and full. Abid defends it really nicely off his front foot.
Better line and length this. On the good length area and outside off, Abid leaves it alone.

Down the leg side. Abid looks to flick but misses. Looks like they are intentionally bowling one or two down the leg side to Abid Ali so that he can kiss one of his flick which can go to the keeper. Not sure whether this is a right plan or not.
A Steven Smith-esque leave this. Fuller outside off, Abid leaves it alone in an unorthodox manner.
Good length ball outside off, asking Abid to have a crack at it but he shoulders arms to it.
Very good ball this. Very full, almost a yorker around off. Abid does really well to jam it out towards mid on.
Beauty to end with. Back of a length delivery around off, it looks to go with the angle but straightens after hitting the deck. Shan looks to defend but gets beaten.

Pakistan get their scoreboard underway, albeit a leg bye. Slightly fuller and angling in. Abid looks to flick but misses. The ball goes to the leg side off the pads. There is a slight appeal but the umpire turns it down as it is doing too much and in the meantime they steal a leg bye.
Good length ball which comes in to the right-hander. It is around the pads, Ali looks to flick but misses and gets hit on the pads.
Right off the meat! Good length ball on off, Abid shows that he is a man in form as he defends it right of the middle of the blade towards cover.
Another one down the leg side and once again Abid tries to flick but to no avail.

A bit of noise there. Not sure whether it was of the ball clipping the pad or the bat hitting the pad. Kumara starts with a length ball down the leg side, Abid looks to flick but misses. Dickwella behind the stumps dives to his left but fails to take it cleanly. Wouldn't have mattered as the ball did not kiss the bat.
Lahiru Kumara to bowl from the other end.
Maiden to start with. Tidy start from Vishwa. The last ball is fuller around off, Shan strokes it towards point. The fielder there dives to his left and saves runs for his side.
Good length ball on the pads, Masood looks to flick it to the on side but closes the phase of the bat early and it goes back to the bowler off the leading edge.
Good length ball on off, Masood defends it back to the bowler and shouts a loud no to his partner.
Good length ball outside off, Vishwa wants Shan to drive but Masood is happy to watch it carry to the keeper.
Goes outside off and makes it come back in. Masood shows awareness of his off pole and shoulders arms to it.
Vishwa starts with a fuller delivery on off. Masood starts his innings with a solid front foot defense. Hint of shape first up for Vishwa.

We are all set to begin! The Sri Lankan players are out in a huddle before they take their position in the field. Shan Masood and Abid Ali walk out to open the innings for the hosts. Vishwa Fernando to start the proceedings with the new ball. Masood to take the strike. Three slips and a gully. Here we go!

Just before the start, Pakistan's bowling coach Waqar Younis is caught down for a quick chat with Danny Morrison. Waqar Yonis hopes that his boys enjoy as much as he does. Reminds us that he made his debut and tells us that there is something on offer for the pacers and he hopes that his bowlers can do a good job. Tells that they knew that rain would play a part and there was a bit of a grass and hence they went with 4 pacers. Waqar says that they are bringing back Yasir Shah and he is hopeful that he can do a good job as he has done in the past. Tells their bowlers are a work in progress as they are young and he expects them to become a force to reckon with in the next 6 months or a year.

Sri Lanka (Playing XI) - Dimuth Karunaratne (C), Oshada Fernando, Kusal Mendis, Dinesh Chandimal, Angelo Mathews, Dhananjaya de Silva, Niroshan Dickwella (WK), Dilruwan Perera, Lasith Embuldeniya (In for Kasun Rajitha), Vishwa Fernando, Lahiru Kumara.

Pakistan (Playing XI) - Shan Masood, Abid Ali, Azhar Ali (C), Babar Azam, Haris Sohail, Asad Shafiq, Mohammad Rizwan (WK), Yasir Shah (In for Usman Shinwari), Mohammad Abbas, Naseem Shah, Shaheen Afridi.
TOSS - Pakistan skipper, Azhar Ali has the coin in hand. Up it goes and it comes down in the hosts' favour. PAKISTAN OPT TO BAT!

After rain and bad lights played spoilsport in Test cricket's return to Rawalpindi, it is time for Test cricket to return to Karachi. Centuries from debutant, Abid Ali and Babar Azam showed why Pakistan can never be counted out. They would look to repeat the same heroics with the bat. On the bowling end of things, the hosts will be forced to make a change as Usman Shinwari is ill so it will be interesting to see if the hosts replace him with leg spinner Yasir Shah or once again surprise everyone and go without a proper spinner. Coming to the visitors, in the one inning they batted they would be disappointed with their collapse and Dimuth Karunaratne will hope that his troops can correct it. Their bowling was lacklustre and looked void of ideas and they will need to find a way to improve that. It will be interesting to see how many changes the tourists make for this one. With the series and 60 points in the ICC World Test Championship up for grabs who will come out on top in this tasty encounter?

So the bowlers have done their job, the hosts will now need to better their performance with the bat as it won't be an easy task to cross the deficit especially with the new ball moving under lights. Sri Lanka will look to take advantage of the new cherry and will look to strike early. Who will succeed? Join us in a bit to find out.

As for Pakistan's bowling, Mohammad Abbas and Shaheen Afridi were the stars. The latter was impressive and rightfully bagged his maiden fifer. He will remember this for a long, long time. Abbas too bowled beautifully and hardly gave away any freebies. Naseem Shah bowled really well but did not get rewards for his effort. Haris Sohail picked the important wicket of Chandimal. But it was another bad day for Yasir Shah. It has been a very bad year for him and he went wicketless. But overall the bowlers can be satisfied with their efforts.

Sri Lanka have been bowled out for 271 and they will be very happy with their efforts. At one stage with the score reeling at 80/5, it looked like the visitors would struggle to get close to Pakistan's total but 50+ stands between Chandimal and Dhananjaya and then Chandimal and Dilruwan Perera ensured they cross the hosts total with ease. Chandimal was the best batter as his 74 ensured they did not succumb. Special mention to Dilruwan Perera as well for his 48 took the lead to 80.

OUT! Timber! Five-fer for Afridi as he hits the top of off, first one in Tests for Shaheen. Kumara cannot add anything to the lead. Good length ball on off, Kumara looks to defend coming forward but misses the line of the ball. It goes behind and hits the top of off. That will be end of the Lankan innings.
Fuller one on middle, Kumara keeps it out.
Lahiru Kumara is the last man in.

OUT! LBW! The review will not help Perera. He misses out on a well deserved half ton. Afridi bowls a pacy ball around middle and leg, Dilruwan looks to flick but he is early into the shot. It hits him flush on the pads and Afridi makes a loud appeal. The umpire raises the finger instantly. Perera too signals the 'T' without taking any time. Can the DRS save him? Let's find out. Front foot is okay. No willow, confirms the Ultra Edge. Here comes the Ball Tracker. Pitching in line. Hitting the wickets? No, but it is clipping the wickets, which means umpire's call stays and Perera has to depart for 48. A top innings though from him to help Pakistan take a good lead.

Perera has been given out LBW. Perera though goes for the review straightaway. Let's see if the DRS can save him. Front foot first, it is fine. No bat there, confirms Ultra Edge. Here comes the Ball Tracker. Pitching in line and umpire's call on hitting the wicket. Perera has to walk off.
Fuller around off, driven to mid off.
Beaten! Beautifully bowled! It is slightly shortish around off, it then comes in and cuts Perera into half. Lucky not to get an inside edge on that one.
Fuller and on middle, Vishwa tucks it towards mid-wicket to see off the over.
Landed on middle, it is worked towards deep square leg for a single.
Fullish length around off, it is blocked off the back foot.
Sprays down the leg side this time. Fernando lets it go to the keeper.
Another one! It is outside off, Fernando has no problems ducking under it.
Another bouncer! Fernando sways away from it nicely. Called wide.
Hit wicket? No, just safe! That was a bouncer which did not rise enough. Fernando tried to duck under it but fell in the process. Does well to keep himself away from the stumps at the very end.
Shortish on middle, Perera taps it towards backward point and thinks for a single. Perera though it not interested.
Bouncer! Perera ducks it away.

FOUR! Now down the ground! Slightly overpitched around off, Dilruwan this time gets on top of the bounce and creams it through mid on. Afridi tries to get his hand down but could not get it. Perera moves to 48.
FOUR! Guided it nicely! Poor line from Shaheen. It is on the pads, Perera just clips it to the fine leg fence and moves to 44.
In the channel outside off, it is left alone.
Bouncer on middle! Dilruwan ducks under it.
Outside off, it is left alone.
On the pads on a fullish length, Perera flicks but makes no connection. It goes towards mid-wicket and they take a leg bye.
Play and a miss! Another good length ball outside off, Perera throws his bat to get beaten.
Shortish around off, Perera cuts but gets an inside edge onto the pads.

Dropped! A tough chance though this one for the skipper!  A slower one outside off, Fernando just checks his shot towards covers. The ball goes towards Azhar at extra cover who throws his left hand to catch but it just does not stick. It goes behind and a single taken.
On middle, Vishwa tucks it towards square leg off the back foot.
On a good length on off, Dilruwan blocks it off the front foot.
Bowls it down the leg side, Perera looks to flick but misses it.
Full delivery outside off, Fernando drives it through covers. The fielder chases it and does well to stop it. The batsmen get three runs.
Good length delivery on leg, Fernando looks to flick but gets hit on the pads.
On a good length on off, Vishwa defends it out.
Full delivery on middle, Fernando defends it off the back foot.

NOT OUT! No bat! A review lost for Pakistan. Shortish length ball down the leg side. Perera looks to flick but misses. Rizwan behind the wicket pouches the ball and appeals instantly. The umpire is not interested. Rizwan is sure though that there was some noise. He convinces his skipper and they go for the DRS. Let's see what the replays confirm. First, the front foot, it is fine. Ultra Edge time, flat line, it is as it passes the bat. Then a line appears, it is of the ball kissing the thigh pad. One review done and dusted for the hosts.

Pakistan have taken a review for caught behind. It is a ball down the leg side, Dilruwan looks to flick but the ball goes off something to the left of the keeper. Rizwan asks the question but Abbas is unsure. Rizwan tells his teammates that he has heard a noise but he is not sure what it came off. Azhar Ali takes it upstairs as they have both their reviews left. Let's see what the replays have to say. Replay rolls in and it shows that there was no bat involved. The ball kissed his thigh pad and that was the noise. Pakistan lose their review.
Fuller and on middle, it is defended.
Good length ball outside off, Vishwa guides it through gully for a single.
Fuller and around off, Perera flicks it towards deep mid-wicket and calls for a couple. However, Fernando was slow to take off for the first run so just a single.
Short ball outside off, Perera cuts but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Good length ball on middle, Perera looks to flick but misses. A stifled appeal but nothing from the umpire.
Second new ball time.
On off and on a fuller length ball. It is defended.
Bouncer again! Another bumper which is aimed at the head. Vishwa, somehow manages to sway away. Lucky not to get hit. Could've been very risky as he took his eyes off the ball.
Bouncer! Shortish ball outside off, Vishwa does well but sways away.
Fuller and around off, Fernando blocks it nicely once again.
Full and on middle this time, Vishwa digs it out nicely.
Shaheen starts with a ball around off, it is blocked.
Shaheen Afridi to bowl from the other end.
Full and on the pads, tucked towards mid-wicket.
On middle, pushed towards mid-wicket.
FOUR! Poor line and punished! A full ball down the leg side, Dilruwan clips it to the fine leg fence nicely.
On the pads this time, Perera tucks it towards fine leg and looks for a single first but later decides against it.
Shortish around off, pushed towards point.
Short and outside off, Perera punches it through cover-point. Single denied  as there is protection in the deep.

We are back for the final session of the day. The Pakistan players are out in the middle. Dilruwan Perera and Vishwa Fernando will resume their innings for the visitors. Mohammad Abbas will start the proceedings for the final session.
... Day 2, Session 3 ...

Sri Lanka have managed to fight out this session and one has to credit them for their efforts. They have taken their lead to 60 and have two wickets in hand. Niroshan Dickwella went out early in the session but Chandimal and Dilruwan Perera countered and the duo added 51 runs to take the lead to 44. After the loss of Chandimal, Dilruwan has kept majority of the strikes and is looking to score quick runs. Abbas and Haris Sohail were the one to get into the wickets column. How long will the visitors bat and till how much can they extend their lead? Join us after the break to find out.
On a good length on middle, Fernando blocks it off the back foot. THAT WILL BE TEA ON DAY 2!
Bowls a yorker on middle, Vishwa does well to dig it out.
On a good length on off, Fernando defends it off the front foot.
Length delivery on middle, Perera defends it towards mid-wicket. The batsmen cross ends.
Full delivery on middle, Perera drives it through mid on but does not take the single.
Length delivery on off, Perera taps it to point.
NO BALL! Afridi oversteps! Bowls a bouncer, Perera does well to duck under it.
On a good length on off, Vishwa keeps it out.
Bowls a bouncer, Fernando does well to duck under it.
On a length on off, Perera taps it towards covers and takes a quick single.
Full delivery on middle, Perera drives it uppishly towards mid on but does not take the single.
Good length delivery on off, Dilruwan defends it off the back foot.
On a length on middle, Perera flicks it towards the leg side.
Mohammad Abbas is back on. 22-9-46-4 are his figures so far.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.

Fuller and outside off, Perera drives but gets an under edge which both first slip and the wicket keeper cannot collect. It goes between them just outside the ring. The batters take off the single. The first slip fielder gets to the ball and aims a throw at the striker's end but misses. Had he hit, Fernando would've been gone.

NOT OUT! Umpire's call on hitting the wickets which means Perera survives to continue swelling the Lankan lead. Let's talk about the ball. It is a shortish length just outside off, Perera looks to defend it off the back foot but misses to get hit on the pads. The bowler and the slip cordon appeals but not out says the umpire. Shaheen though is sure as he asks the skipper to go for the DRS. And he then eventually himself signals it to the umpire. Let's see what the replays show. The front foot is okay. Time for Ultra Edge, nothing on it. Ball Tracker time. Here it comes, It is just clipping the bails of off and middle. Umpire's call it will be then, on hitting the stumps. So, Perera stays. Pakistan keep their review.

Appeal for LBW taken upstairs. Dilruwan is the man in question. It seemed like Afridi forced his captain to go for the review instantly. The skipper quickly obliged. Looks high to the naked eye. Let's see the replays. The front foot is fine. No edge, confirms the Ultra Edge. The Ball Tracker rolls in now. Clipping the stumps so umpire's call it will be. Dilruwan will continue.
FOUR! Flicked nicely! Full and on the pads, Perera flicks it to deep mid-wicket for a boundary.
Shortish length outside off, Perera taps it through point. It goes towards sweeper cover but he denies a single. Looking for quick runs while farming the strike?
Bouncer to start the new spell. Perera ducks under it.
Shaheen Afridi is back on. 21-4-59-3 so far from him.
Loopy delivery on off, Vishwa defends it off the front foot.
Floated delivery on middle, Fernando blocks it off the back foot.
Tossed up delivery on off, Perera drives it towards mid off for a run.
Flighted delivery on middle, Perera defends it off the back foot.
Short delivery on off, Perera cuts it to point.
SIX! This is out of here. Someone please give the ball back. Floated on the stumps, Dilruwan comes down the track and smokes it over the bowler's head for a biggie. The lead now over 50!
Flighted around off, blocked off the back foot.
Around off and middle, it is defended towards mid-wicket.

NOT OUT! That bounced just in front of Shafiq's hand. So, the third umpire has changed the soft signal, which means he was sure, absolutely sure. Took a lot of time but eventually gave the benefit of doubt to the Lankan batter. It was a flighted ball just outside off, Fernando drives but the ball takes a thick outside edge and goes to Shafiq at first slip. He catches and celebrates. The umpire is not sure though as they refer it upstairs. The third umpire checks with various angles and then eventually finds it bouncing just in front of the fingers. So, Fernando survives.

Did that carry? The soft signal is out. Let's see what the replays show. That looks to be bouncing just in front of Shafiq at first slip. The third umpire is taking his time. Need to have conclusive evidence to turn the decision.
Floated delivery on middle, Perera flicks it towards square leg for a run.
Flighted delivery on off, Perera looks to defend but gets an outside edge. It goes towards first slip on one bounce.
Tossed up delivery on off, Dilruwan defends it off the front foot.
Flighted around off, Vishwa looks to defend but gets hit on the pads. The short leg fielder pouches the ball and appeals but nothing from the umpire.
Vishwa Fernando is the next batsman in.

OUT! Caught! The part-timer strikes. Not the perfect ball at all but he has got the massive wicket of Chandimal. Short and just outside off, Dinesh goes for the cut. He ends up slicing it towards Shan Masood at backward point who makes no mistake. End of a very good knock from Chandimal. He could've swelled the lead to a bigger one, so a very important wicket this one.
The batsman works it down the leg side. They pick up a single.
Full and around off, Perera strokes to long off for a single. 50-run stand is up between the two.
Short around off, stroked straight to cover.
Fuller one on the pads, Perera flicks but misses to get hit on the pad. It hits the pad and goes towards square leg for a leg bye.
Loopy ball around off, pushed towards the extra cover fielder once again.
Full and on off, pushed back to the bowler.
Full and outside off, Chandimal drives it well but finds short extra cover.
Floated around off on a fuller length, defended towards covers.
Another flatter one outside off, tapped towards point by Chandimal.
Quicker one and outside off, pushed to long off for a single.
Yasir Shah is back on. 11-0-41-0 are his figures so far.
Fuller and down the leg side. Perera looks to flick but misses. The ball hits the pads and goes towards short fine leg for a leg bye.
Flighted and around off, blocked.
Full and on the pads, flicked to mid-wicket.
Flighted and fuller around off, Dinesh eases it through mid off for a single.
Flatter one around off, Perera looks to defend but the ball hits the upper part of the bat and goes towards point uppishly. A single.

... Day 2, Session 2 ...

So, the 2 hour 40 minute session is done and we now have an extended break for prayers. The Lunch break will be for 1 hour. What do we have in store for the second session? Will Pakistan come good and wrap it up for under 200 or will Sri Lanka get a significant lead? Join us after the break to find out.

Pakistan will be disappointed with their effort. They started off well but that partnership between Dhananjaya de Silva and Chandimal dented their morale. Abbas and Shaheen have been the pick of the bowlers and have 3 wickets each. Naseem too bowled well but the cause of concern for the hosts would be the ease with Yasir Shah has been played with. Azhar Ali would want his spinner to come good and help out the trio of pace bowlers.

End of the extended session. It was a very even session but in the context of this game, Sri Lanka will be happier as the trail is now just 21. It looked like Pakistan might be able to restrict them under their score of 191 when the tourists were stuttering at 80/5 but a 67-run stand between Chandimal and Dhananjaya de Silva ensured that Sri Lanka do not falter badly. The centurion from the last game though could not convert his start but Chandimal looks set and he is joined by Dickwella. The onus will be on these two as this is the last recognized batting pair for them.

Sri Lanka coach Mickey Arthur is caught down for a quick chat with Roshan Abheysinghe. Sri Lanka coach Mickey Arthur says that he does not think that it was a good toss to lose. Tells it will be very difficult to bat in the fourth innings and he would have liked to bat first as well. Tells they have chance to bat well and take charge of the game. Says they are aware of how good Yasir Shah is and they will need to be careful. Adds they have good experienced players coming in and they need to be really good. On the surface, he says it is a good Test wicket which has runs in it but also says there is something for the bowlers in it.

Trail - 127. Wickets in hand - 7. That's where the visitors are at the start of this beautiful day in Karachi. Hello and welcome to the coverage of Day 2 of the second Test between Pakistan and Sri Lanka.  The visitors are slightly on the front foot but will need to bat really well and try and get some significant lead in this bowler friendly wicket. They'd hope to avoid a collapse unlike their counterparts and get a further grip on this game. Pakistan, on the other hand, are well and truly in this game. They know a few early blows in the day will put the tourists under pressure and they would look to do just that. The pitch has turn and bounce on offer and we are yet to see Yasir Shah and anyone who has followed Pakistan's Test side in the recent past knows how lethal he can be. So the ball dominated the bat on Day 1 will the story continue or will it will be the chance of the willow to shine? What's in store? Stay tuned to find out.
... Day 2, Session 1 ...

So clearly a day that belonged to the bowlers but what do we have in store on Day 2? The visitors trail by 127 runs, a glance at it and you'd feel that it is a small total but this pitch has demons of its own and it is not easy to score runs. Will it get tougher on Day 2? Join us on Friday at 1000 Local (0500 GMT), to know how this game pans out. Join us for Day 2. Till then, cheers!

After a watchful start with the bat, Pakistan did manage to make their mark with the ball. They needed wickets and they managed to get three including the big wicket of Dimuth Karunaratane. Only 3 pacers were used and Abbas was the pick of them picking up a couple while Shaheen had one. Giving the hosts a hope and chance of a fightback.

The hosts won the toss and elected to bat but it was a decision that backfired as apart from Abid Ali, Babar Azam and Asad Shafiq none of the batters got into double figures. And from 127/3 they were wrapped up for just 191. The scorecard had some respectability courtesy of fifties from Babar and Asad.

What a day of cricket it was. It did not have runs but the bowlers have had a good day. 13 wickets have fallen in the day and that in itself tells the story. This match is evenly poised so far, Sri Lanka have their noses in front but only just.

Well, here comes the breaking news. PAKISTAN HAVE DECLARED during the Lunch break. Bizarre, very bizarre. One understands that the bowlers need time to take wickets but declaring during a break is very strange. Normally, captains declare minutes to go into the break, or having played for a while after the break. This is normally done so that the openers do not get time to make themselves ready. Azhar Ali is a kind guy. So Sri Lanka need 476 to win or hang around for 153 overs.

50 overs for Lasith Embuldeniya. He has toiled. But without much purpose. There is no zip off the surface but he has barely been consistent with his line or length. Lahiru Kumara has been the only bowler who has bowled decently while the rest have just 'put it there'. They will hope to get to bat soon. Join us back at 12.40 pm local (0740 GMT) to see what happens.

On a pitch which is as flat as a highway, nothing less than a century can be expected and Pakistan batsmen did not disappoint. Azhar Ali and Babar Azam continued from where they left off, almost managing a wicketless session before the need to up the ante got Azhar Ali to throw his wicket away. Mentioning about the lead is almost redundant - a paltry 475. Runs are not important at this stage and Pakistan will only be looking to bat for time. Perhaps a declaration an hour after Lunch.

160/1 in 27 overs. What a session for Pakistan. Sri Lanka would be relieved with the break. It has been a continuous pummelling and if they are not morally down by now, they will be soon. Clearly, they are waiting for the declaration.

Sri Lanka's bowling coach, Rumesh Ratnayake, is having a chat with Roshan Abeysinghe. Admits that from here on, Sri Lanka only need to focus on delaying Pakistan's run-plan. Agrees that the bowlers erred on Saturday but does not want to take anything away from the Pakistan batters. Stresses that apart from Lahiru Kumara, no one bowled consistent lines and lengths. Hopes that the other bowlers take some learnings from Kumara's effort and do well this morning. Is amazed with Lahiru's consistent pace and even more, his fitness.

The reason for the previous paragraph is that nothing happened on Saturday. NOTHING. The ball did not swing, neither did it seam, nor did it turn. The track looked as flat as a pancake and Pakistan made merry. Given that they scored at a brisk rate, they have got themselves in a position from where they cannot lose. Or should not. However, if the maintenance is on track of this highway, you cannot rule out a draw. Day 4 is usually where the pitches start to turn in Asia. Let's see.

Day 1. Bang, bang, bang, bang, bang! Day 2. Bang, bang, bang. Day 3. Snoreeeeeeeeeeeeeeee. That is how this Test match has been unfolding. Looking at the first two days, one felt that this game will not last beyond the third day. But looking at Pakistan's resurgence, it seems like the clock will tick past 5 pm on Monday, but we might still not get a result. Can Day 4 prove us wrong? Hello and a warm welcome to the second Test between Pakistan and Sri Lanka in Karachi.

What's on the card for the fourth day of this Test then? How long will Pakistan bat? Will Azhar Ali and Babar Azam get to their tons and take Pakistan towards massive lead? Or on a fresh morning, will the Lankans make a comeback with quick strikes? So many questions to be answered. Well, to get to know these answers, join us on Sunday, 22nd December. The play will begin at 1000 local (0500 GMT). Till then, goodbye and take care.

What about the Lankan bowling? Well, they got absolutely nothing from the surface and kept toiling hard. The pacers came charging in and the spinners, Embuldeniya and Perera too bowled well without any success. Lahiru Kumara was their only bowler who managed to pick a couple of scalps but they came quite late as the first session for them went wicketless. Lahiru removed Shan first in the last over before Tea and then struck again to remove Abid Ali in the final session.

What an unbelievable day of Test cricket for Pakistan! They have taken their lead to 315. Their two overnight batters, Shan Masood and Abid Ali raked up their brilliant respective Test tons to take Pakistan to a commanding position. They kept tiring the Lankan bowlers and milked runs with ease. Once the stand was broken, skipper Azhar joined Abid out in the middle and added 77 runs before Abid became the second victim of Kumara. Sri Lanka's misery was far from ending as Babar Azam joined the skipper and added unbeaten 40 runs between them. Azhar is unbeaten on 57 while Babar has looked solid for his 22.

OUT! LBW! Pakistan lose their review but no one can raise a finger on Abid Ali because he has played a gem of a knock. Everyone in the stadium is up on its feet as he walks off. Similar way he got out in the previous innings. Fast and pacy delivery pitching around off. It jags back in, Abid looks to defend but gets beaten by the pace of it and the ball hits him on the pads. Sri Lankan players go up in a huge appeal and the umpire slowly raises his finger. Abid knows he is a goner but after talking to his partner, he signals the 'T' in the eleventh hour. Replay rolls in and Ultra Edge shows there is no involvement of the bat. Ball Tracker then comes in and it shows all red as  the ball was going onto crash the middle stump. To the dismay of everyone, Abid will have to walk back but what a fine player he is. He will be disappointed not to get to his double century. But it has been a great knock and he has put his side in a great position in this game. He walks back looking as fresh as he came out to bat in  the first day of this Test. Though he is 32, he looks like a fine player and one feels he will be a big player for this side for a few years to come.

The Sri Lankan bowlers have toiled hard but have failed to extract much from the surface which looks quite easy to bat on. Lahiru Kumara finally provided them the breakthrough and now, they would hope to see the back of a few batters in the final session of the day. Will the hosts continue their march forward or will the visitors be able to bounce back in the final session of the day? Join us in a while to find out.

29 overs, 107 runs and a wicket! That's how the session has panned out for the hosts. You seeing that one wicket, right. Well, it came at the stroke of tea but not before Pakistan take their lead to 202 runs. Abid Ali, the centurion, from the first game has raked up another unbeaten hundred and he is looking set for a big one. He got brilliant support from Shan Masood from the other end who too smashed a ton but got out just three balls before the break.

Masood is taken by surprise. Maybe he expected Lahiru to be tired and did not expect a short one. He is late in his pull and he ends up hitting it in  the air straight to the man at deep mid-wicket. Oshada Fernando there comes running in and takes a good catch. The 278-run partnership is broken. Pakistan lose their first wicket with the lead of 198.

Tells that it has been 2 days of challenging Test cricket and he is relishing it as he feels it is good to see that the pitch has something for everyone. Says that the key in Test cricket is keeping your discipline and playing on merit is the key. Further adds batsmen need to keep their calm and results will take care of itself. Credits his openers for playing out the tough period and reducing the deficit. Hello and welcome to the coverage of Day 3 of the 2nd Test between Pakistan and Sri Lanka. After having a deficit of 80, the Pakistan openers have done really well to reduce it to just 23 and still have all the 10 wickets in hand. The duo of Abid Ali and Shan Masood will look to continue that this morning as well and their first aim would be to get these 23 runs without losing a wicket. Sri Lanka, on the other hand, will look to improve with the ball. They were very poor with it last evening and need to refocus and revisit their plans. The pitch has started to break just a hint but still it has become a good pitch to bat on. A very important day awaits us in a match where everything is right under the balance.  Will the host score plenty of runs and take the ascendancy in this game or will the visitors once again take the driver's seat? Stay tuned to find out.
... Day 3, Morning Session ...

So, 13 wickets fell on Day 1. 7 fell on Day 2. What does this mean? Is the pitch getting better to bat on? The ease with Pakistan batted in the final session, it seems so. We now move to the crucial Day 3 of this 2nd and final Test between Pakistan and Sri Lanka. What is in store for us on Day 3? Join us on Saturday, 21st December to find out. The play will begin at 1000 local (0500 GMT). Till then, it's goodbye from us!

Earlier in the day, Sri Lanka, after stuttering at 80/5 managed to post 271 on the board, taking a lead of 80 in the process. Dinesh Chandimal was the architect in chief as his 74 along with Dilruwan Perera's 48 helped the visitors go past Pakistan's total of 191. Shaheen Afridi was the star of the show with the ball as he scalped his first five-wicket haul in Test cricket. He was helped by Abbas as well who picked up a 4-fer.

Solid end to the day for the hosts and they have not just managed to get through the day without losing a wicket but they have also managed to reduce the deficit to 23. Abid Ali has once again looked good and Shan has supported him well. They have managed to score at over 4 rpo and this match looks evenly poised. Sri Lanka will be disappointed with their efforts with the ball as they would have liked to have at least one wicket before the end of day's play.

Right. That ends a historic tour of Pakistan by Sri Lanka. Really commendable of them for agreeing to tour the nation and this might just encourage other sides to come here. They will be disappointed but do not have time to dwell on too much on this defeat. Because if this was tough, their next challenge is even tougher. The tour of India which comprises of 3 T20Is. All the best to them to begin 2020 on a good note.

A special moment. Azhar Ali takes the trophy in his hands but he has barely moved a couple of paces before the entire team charges out towards him! They want that trophy. A win in front of your home crowd. The real home. No wonder they are beaming. Congratulations! They are now third in the ICC World Test Championship, earning 80 points but are way behind Australia and India.

Victorious Pakistan captain, Azhar Ali, is beaming. Thanks the almighty and agrees that they needed this win. Thanks the Sri Lankans from the bottom of his heart for travelling to Pakistan and further says that the Lankans have no idea about the happiness given by them to Pakistan cricket fans by this gesture. Coming over to this series, Azhar says that it has been a tough passage of time in the recent past but they wanted to start their home season well. Feels satisfied with this result. On exciting talents in Shaheen Afridi and Naseem Shah, Ali is awed by their skill, especially their ability to learn the art of fast bowling very quickly. Praises all the fast bowlers for coming hard in the first innings after the batsmen got bowled out for 191. Then, he comes to the openers in the second innings, for setting the tone and taking the game away from Sri Lanka. But also finds words of praise for Babar Azam and Asad Shafiq for fighting hard in the first innings. On Pakistan bouncing back in the second innings, Azhar says that is the job of the team management - keep the team calm under pressure - which was done and the effect showed. On his own return to form, Ali is happy to have finally got a big innings after a long time and hopes to carry on this form. On the summary of the two Tests, Azhar wants to take this confidence into away series. Praises the bowlers because no one had an idea how to bowl on Pakistan wickets but adjusting well and quickly. Hopes to build on this confidence now. Thanks the security agencies for their excellent work and also the crowd for turning up in large numbers.

Sri Lankan skipper, Dimuth Karunaratne, manages a smile. Believes that his team dominated on the first two days but then credits Azhar Ali and his side for putting the pressure back on them. Stresses that patience is the key in Tests and that is where Pakistan outplayed them. On the lead of 80 not being good enough, Karunaratne does not agree. He feels it was good enough at that time but then laments the runs given away in the second innings, that too, at a quick rate. Agrees that they got dominated over the last three days. Asked for positives, Dimuth points out to Oshada Fernando's mental toughness with his century, then Dhananjaya de Silva, Niroshan Dickwella and Lahiru Kumara. Wants the others to lift their level up like these four. Thanks the crowd for turning in large numbers and praises the security offered to the players. Hopes to come back to Pakistan again to play cricket.

ABID ALI HAS BEEN NAMED THE MAN OF THE MATCH AND SERIES. Big impact in the first Test. Thanks the almighty for helping him earn this respect. Admits that his hard work in domestic cricket has reaped rich dividends in this historic game. Calls this as a proud moment for him and his family and thanks all his supporters. On his batting confidence, Ali says that he has self-belief and keeps working and staying positive. Adds that he also tries to help others and also tries to improve on his shot selection and work on small technical glitches. On the failure in Australia but doing well here, Abid says that even though the team lost Down Under, they practiced hard and kept trying, believing in one another. Points that to the reason behind this win. Thanks the crowd for turning up here and also in Rawalpindi.
Abid Ali is being given a memento by Zaheer Abbas for becoming the first male cricketer to score centuries on ODI and Test debuts. Terrific feat.

Positives for Sri Lanka - well, the pace bowling in the first innings and Embuldeniya's line and length. Then Dinesh Chandimal's solid innings with the bat. But no consistency in the second dig, apart from Niroshan Dickwella and Oshada Fernando. Pakistan's happiness would be with the fact that two youngsters picked up 5-fers in each innings - Shaheen Afridi and Naseem Shah. Who gets the Man Of The Match though? Here comes the presentation...

A Test match or any format for that matter, is all about taking the opportunities. Sri Lanka had the chance to finish the game on Day 3 itself. They had 14 overs to bowl under fading light on Friday evening (Day 2) but that wicketless passage gave terrific confidence to the hosts. Pakistan grabbed THAT moment. Perhaps at that stage, the Lankans took it lightly. They expected the pitch to offer sideways and lateral movement, including spin but were not consistent at all. Pakistan, on the other hand, knew they had their backs to the wall and had no way to go but ahead. And they went. On and on and on they went. For 131 overs, with the top 4 scoring centuries. Then in the final innings, when Sri Lanka were pushed into a corner, the visitors cowed away.

What was different from the two sides? The approach. In the first dig, Pakistan were nervous and Sri Lanka pounced. But once the home side got over its nerves, they pounced back. It was that moment where the Lankans failed. They had lesser discipline as compared to Pakistan and got a lead of only 80. Yes. Only 80, in hindsight. But at that time, it seemed it was good enough.

16 balls. That is all the Test match lasted on Day 5. A 16-year old has brought smiles to millions of faces in Pakistan. Not sure this was present on the first two days when the hosts folded for 191 and then conceded a lead of 80. But the second innings batting was simply too magnanimous.

Shan Masood is now having a chat with Bazid Khan. On this win, Masood says that the team had a chat before this series and everyone was disappointed with the Adelaide loss. Stresses that everyone had to contribute if the team had to win and feels satisfied that every member of the playing XI contributed in some way or the other. On nervousness about playing an international game for the first time in Pakistan, Masood says that it did reflect in their first innings with the bat but as soon as it sinked in and they settled into it, they came back and performed collectively as a unit. On his opening stand with Abid Ali, Shan says that he and Abid have played a lot of domestic cricket for Islamabad and hence both are familiar with each other. Further says that the talk of the dressing room was to score big which was missing in Australia, apart from Babar Azam. Is happy that 4 batsmen could contribute big. On him being the 'local' lad, Masood smiles and says that he has played for numerous sides so he finds it difficult to choose which region he belongs to. Ends by saying that they will be looking at this break, spend time with their families and then gear up for the next series, which would be Bangladesh (if they agree to come) as they know they have a few important ones lined up.

Bazid Khan is interviewing Waqar Younis. Pakistan's bowling coach says that when he played cricket, it was much different then. But this one, is much emotional, as Test cricket has returned to Pakistan after 10 years. Admits that the entire dressing room had the feeling that it would end quickly this morning and is thankful to the almighty for everything. On Naseem Shah's impressive bowling, Younis honestly feels that these are very early days for the youngster. Lauds him, the management and the selectors but wants to wait and see how the lad develops. Is happy that Shaheen Afridi did well and Mohammad Abbas got back to form. Stresses that in the past, Karachi has always been favourable to pacers. Wants more Tests to be played at home and believes that this unit will take Pakistan cricket a long way. On being asked to compare this series with the ones in the Middle East, Waqar says that it is totally different by using the phrase, 'Home is Home'.

Nothing conclusive from the replays but then Ultra Edge detects glove. Sensational bowling.

The players are out in the middle. Pakistan team gets into a huddle outside the boundary. LASITH EMBULDENIYA has joined Oshada Fernando in the middle. Now, the hosts spread out. Naseem to continue his over from Day 4. Here we go...

Niroshan Dickwella is having a chat with Roshan Abeysinghe. On his knock last evening, Dikka says that he had a chat with Oshada Fernando and made a plan. Stresses that first he played defensively but missed a couple of balls. Then, he adds that he chose to attack. Feels unfortunate that he got out after the century stand but believes that reverse sweep is his strength and he will not stop playing anything which is his strength. Honestly says that the match went away from Sri Lanka on Day 3 and if someone from his team had batted strongly, they might not have been in this situation. On what different they could have done in the second innings with the ball, Niroshan says that they could have maintained more consistency and intensity.

From Pakistan's point of view, they will hope that the young Naseem Shah gets a 5-fer. He has bowled exceptionally well and the way he setup Dilruwan Perera shows the matured head on his young shoulders. He will be raring to bowl fast this morning and clean this up in a jiffy.

Since Day 2 evening, it has all been Pakistan. Sunday was no different. Barring that one fightback from Oshada Fernando and Niroshan Dickwella, there was nothing much from Sri Lanka. They trail by a mammoth 263 runs and even if they stave off 64 off those, it will be an achievement, considering that only 3 wickets are left.

That time when you feel should we even go to the ground? Should we even switch on the television sets? Shall we just wait for the inevitable update to come which will read Pakistan win the game? With due respect to Sri Lanka, does not seem like there will be any fightback coming this morning. 3 wickets remaining and they might just hope to delay what is going to be the eventual result. Will we even get an hour of play? Hello and a warm welcome to the final day of Sri Lanka's tour of Pakistan.

What is remaining for Sri Lanka in this Test match? Just hope that there is some solid fight shown. But sadly, there are no batting pairs left. Oshada Fernando is the only recognized batsman remaining and given that three tail-enders are to come, this might not last even 30 minutes on Day 5. Join us at 10 am local (0500 GMT) for the final rites of the match and series. ADIOS! TAKE CARE!

Excellent bowling from Pakistan. On a track where the Lankans toiled and toiled and toiled, struggling to pick wickets for over 2 days, they managed to eke out the edges and got the scalps. Naseem Shah and Shaheen Afridi showed that pace matters as the Lankans were caught hopping in the crease. The 16-year old Naseem will be hoping he gets at least two out of the remaining three wickets, if not all three, for his maiden Test 5-for.

Another day which has belonged to the hosts. They stamped their authority right from the first ball of Day 4 and hammered 160 runs in the opening session. Then, to everyone's surprise, they declared during the Lunch break, catching everyone off guard. The result of that was having the Lankans 5 down for 97 but a rearguard 104-run stand between Dickwella and Oshada has taken this into the fifth day.

One has got to feel for Niroshan Dickwella and Oshada Fernando. The duo did well to almost see off the entire session but with 13 minutes left in the day's play, Dickwella fell and in the final over, Dilruwan perished. Sri Lanka may not have had a realistic chance of winning this but had they got both Oshada and Dickwella in on Monday, they might have made a better attempt in making Pakistan earn their win.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! A wicket and that will be it for the day! Naseem gets his third and Pakistan are just 3 wickets away from a win. Although, they will need to come on Day 5 to earn that. A typical tail-ender's dismissal. 'Oh dear. He hit me in the previous ball. Will he fire a bouncer now? It is a bit dark.' Naseem reads all of these. He smartly bowls a length ball, which is slightly wide outside off. What is so smart about that, do you ask? Mind games. Perera is in two minds whether to play or leave and since this is on a length, thinks he can play. Pushes at the wide one and edges it behind. Naseem is jubilant. What a setup to the tail-ender. Ooohh... another edge. Does not carry. This is an exciting passage of play. A length ball outside off, moving away, Mathews looks to defend but the ball moves away, takes the outside edge and lands short of gully.
Full delivery on middle, Mathews drives it through mid on for a run.

NOT OUT! On a good length on middle, Mathews plays it towards point and takes off for a quick single. The fielder picks the ball and fires a throw at the keeper's end which ricochets and goes towards mid-wicket as overthrows. It is referred upstairs. The replays show that the batsman was well in. The batsmen also take an extra run.
Direct hit! Looks to be safe though. Still, referred upstairs. Oshada is the man in potential danger. Here comes the replay. The bat is grounded when the ball hits the stumps.
On a good length on off, Mathews defends it off the back foot.
Angelo Mathews comes in at number 4, replacing Mendis.

OUT! CAUGHT! Now Naseem Shah strikes and gets the second wicket for the hosts. Mendis flops again. On a good length and outside off, Mendis looks to drive but again, no footwork on offer. The ball moves away and takes the outside edge. It goes towards third slip where Babar Azam takes a simple catch.
Good length delivery on middle, Mendis keeps it out.
On a good length on off, Fernando defends it towards the off side and takes a quick single. The fielder goes for a direct hit at the bowler's end but misses it.
A length ball outside off, coming in, Mendis looks to defend but the ball comes in a long way and hits him on the pads. Abbas thinks about appealing but then bails out. Looked to be high.
Full and around off, coming in, watchfully defended.
Kusal Mendis comes in at number 3, replacing his skipper.

OUT! Edged and taken! There goes the first. Sri Lanka took more than 68 overs to take their first wicket in the third innings. Pakistan have taken less than 68 balls - 58 to be precise. Loose from the captain. Nothing special about the delivery and a pretty ordinary shot in reply. Pitched outside off, just straightening a touch, Karunaratne is stuck in the crease as he plays a loose waft. Does so well away from his body and gets a thick outside edge. The edge threatens to go between the keeper and first slip but Mohammad Rizwan dives to his left and takes a stunner. In the last 5-10 minutes, it did seem like a wicket was around the corner. And Karunaratne has struck for Pakistan. Yes. Karunaratne. He alone is responsible for his dismissal.

EDGED, FOUR! Ahhh... hands on heads. A length ball outside off, Karunaratne pushes at it away from his body and gets a thick outside edge. The ball goes past a diving gully fielder to the third man fence.
The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.
Full and around off, watchfully defended.
Full delivery on middle, Oshada flicks it through square leg. The batsmen get two runs.
On a length on middle, Karunaratne flicks it through mid-wicket. The batsmen take a single.
Full delivery outside off, Dimuth drives it through covers. The batsmen get two runs.
Good length delivery on off, Dimuth blocks it off the front foot.

Full delivery on leg, Fernando looks to flick but misses it and gets hit on the pads. The bowler appeals for lbw but the umpire shakes his head. Pakistan think of a review but decide against it. Ball Tracker shows that it is umpire's call and it is clipping the leg stump.
Naseem bowls it down the leg side, Fernando looks to flick but misses it.

Naseem Shah is into the attack. Looks like there is some issue straightaway. Naseem is not happy with something around the landing area. And yes, the umpire has called for the hammer. This is a joke. Naseem is not happy with what the groundstaff is doing. So, he himself takes the hammer and starts hammering! Umpire Joel Wilson has a laugh. Now, Naseem comes running in, tries his runup and is happy. We are set to resume now.

Full and outside off, watchfully defended.
Landed outside off, a touch wide, left alone.
Mohammad Abbas to bowl from the other end. Got a 4-fer in the first innings.
Off the mark, is Dimuth. Full and around middle, DK looks to flick but the ball goes off the inner half, past short leg. A couple taken to square leg. Two runs taken.
